#speaker("Dawai", [
Yeah, just like we would if all of a sudden the dreamer became the head that's having the dream (metaphorically speaking) and now it's resting as the head; the whole dream can still be there. Every iota of the dream: the dirt on the ground, the emotions, the squirrels in the trees, the rabbits, the bananas, the dogs. All of it. And that's what we're actually... in my interpretation of radical Dzogchen versus perhaps Keith Dowman, I think is relatively saying the same thing: is that we're so inclusive of everything. There are no more scapegoats; there's no one to blame anything on anymore. We can't even be regretful about anything because that's a contraction away from presence. 

So it's this radical inclusivity that separates this path out and where everything like Guru Rinpoche and Yeshé Tsogyal in their dialogue would say, everything is a kind of training ground. Everything's a teacher; everything's a revelation. Ultimately I think it becomes a kind of... is "revelatory" a word? I'm just going to use that. All right.

So all of a sudden it becomes a revelatory occasion rather than an imputation or an inference. So you're constantly relaxing into this revelation. And then it's not really a revelation: who's it being revealed to? Where's it being revealed from? So words are always going to miss something, but I think you get what I'm saying. The radical aspect would be to include your neighbor, your harsh encounters and tough situations, poking yourself in the eye, stubbing your toe.

And since we do a little bit of work with the clear light and light rays, it gives us an advantage, where normally the reification of our sensory environment can be very convincing. And we can measure that subscription when we go to sleep and we have a dream. Well, how much are we invested? How much did it feel like we were convinced by that, hypnotized by those appearances? And my guess, my theory, my speculation would be that when you go to sleep, however much you're invested—almost as if it was a percentage, if you're 70% invested, it felt like that was a psychic weight.

Maybe as a humorous metaphor you could say how much the dog kicks its leg. And so then all of a sudden you're doing the awareness practice, integrating day and night, and then it feels like 30%. Like, "I was kind of watching that one"; I didn't get emotionally... I didn't have emotional excitations or mental ruminations that typically are like add-ons rather than any kind of analysis. Because if you leave your mind clear, the dream can echo out actually when you wake up, and you'll have revelation there. It's revelatory.

In a multi-layer way you can say: "Oh yeah, I just realized." You know, maybe you're brushing your teeth: "I just realized I was dreaming of an apple tree last night." That's how it works, doesn't it? You don't even try; the recall is natural. But then you also see: "Wow, that apple tree represented my childhood home." You get to see the allegorical underbelly, which I think is the most interesting.

Yeah, it's an exciting topic, you know, the one that I kind of said we're going to venture into this year: the five lights, how the elements are reifications of the mind... exploring that. And so, but like I was saying, I think however much you're kicking your leg in that dream is how much you're kicking your leg in the waking state. That's how much you're subscribed into the waking state.
